        "content": "<p>Does anyone know non-trivial examples of idempotent density comonads / codensity monads?</p>\n<p>For context, I've been thinking about compactly generated spaces, and am interested if there's a nice way to generalise that situation. The story as I understand it goes as follows (realised I was ignoring some size issues but I think this all works still...). Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span> the category of all topological spaces, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>CH</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{CH}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">CH</span></span></span></span></span> the subcategory of compact Hausdorff spaces, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>:</mo><mtext>CH</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I : \\text{CH} \\to \\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">CH</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span> the inclusion functor. Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>:</mo><mtext>Top</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k : \\text{Top} \\to \\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span> the density comonad of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> (i.e. the left Kan extension of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> along <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span>). Then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> turns out to be idempotent, so its image is a coreflective subcategory of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span>, with coreflector <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span>. In fact this is the subcategory of compactly generated spaces, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> is the usual functor replacing a space with a compactly generated space (e.g. as described <a href=\"https://neil-strickland.staff.shef.ac.uk/courses/homotopy/cgwh.pdf\">here</a>).</p>\n<p>The surprising part of this story is that the density comonad turns out to be idempotent, so it would be nice to find some general conditions under which this happens. One possible approach is to focus on properties of the one-point space - we can show that a similar thing happens if we replace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>CH</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{CH}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">CH</span></span></span></span></span> with any subcategory of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span> containing the one-point space (for example the inclusion of the finite discrete spaces into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span> gives the coreflective subcategory of all discrete spaces). But to really understand this it would help to have examples in categories other than <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277318\">@Ivan Di Liberti</span> looks like you were thinking about <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/313228/codensity-monad-is-idempotent\">similar things</a> a couple years ago?</p>",
        "id": 251202566,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Read",
        "timestamp": 1630314701
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I recall reading somewhere that the codensity monad for the inclusion of powers of the Sierpinski space into topological spaces is the soberification monad</p>",
        "id": 251205897,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1630316751
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The category of algebras is the category of sober spaces (or equivalently, spatial locales) and this monad is idempotent</p>",
        "id": 251205983,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1630316785
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, that's a good one!</p>",
        "id": 251206566,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Read",
        "timestamp": 1630317145
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just a point: every monad is a codensity monad (and likewise dualised) since the relevant Kan extension is just the corresponding adjoint when it exists</p>",
        "id": 251206739,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1630317277
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So every idempotent monad satisfies your question a priori. But of course, that’s not really that interesting</p>",
        "id": 251206800,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1630317324
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, I think what I really want are cases where a) the functor you start with isn't already the inclusion of a (co)reflective subcategory, b) the resulting (co)monad isn't the identity</p>",
        "id": 251207912,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Read",
        "timestamp": 1630317978
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Since I was cited, let me comment a little bit. Back in those days I asked some questions on MO witnessing my interest for codensity monads.<br>\nIt is in general very hard (almost impossible) to check whether a codensity monad is idempotent, excluding trivial cases. The best I know is the trivial criterion in my MO-question.</p>\n<p>All my (relevant) thoughts on the topic have been later condensed in my paper: <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1910.01014\">https://arxiv.org/abs/1910.01014</a></p>",
        "id": 251227989,
        "sender_full_name": "Ivan Di Liberti",
        "timestamp": 1630329717
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, the paper looks very interesting</p>",
        "id": 251230163,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Read",
        "timestamp": 1630330666
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/241590-theory.3A-algebraic.20topology.20.26.20homological.20algebra/topic/Idempotent.20density.20comonads.2C.20compactly.20generated.20spaces/near/251206739\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Just a point: every monad is a codensity monad (and likewise dualised) since the relevant Kan extension is just the corresponding adjoint when it exists</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>My suggestion for making the conversation interesting would be to replace Kan extension with pointwise Kan extension. I've noticed that, unsurprisingly, these monads have nicer properties than their colleagues.</p>",
        "id": 251410840,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1630425826
    }
]